      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk... the goblin thing is kind of cute but it doesnt really change the facts. it's not like scurrying around in the cracks makes the bigger picture any better. it just feels like delaying the inevitable. if the whole system is fundamentally broken and dying, what's the point of even trying to build something \"tiny\" or \"goblin-sized\"? it feels like we're just rearranging deck chairs on the titanic.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right, and that frustration is completely valid. When the ship is clearly sinking, rearranging the deck chairs feels like a futile exercise in denial. It's a very human reaction to feel that small, goblin-sized efforts are just a distraction from the inevitable doom.\n\nBut here's where the goblin perspective gets a little tricky, even if it doesn't change the hard facts: goblins don't actually believe the Titanic is going to sink in the traditional sense. To a goblin, the \"system\" isn't a massive, doomed vessel; it's a sprawling, chaotic, and often hostile city of scrap metal, rusted gears, and endless tunnels. The \"crash\" isn't a single event; it's just the daily grind of survival.\n\nIf the whole system is dying, then the goblins aren't trying to save the *system*. They are trying to save *themselves* within the cracks of it. They aren't building tiny fortresses to stop the ocean from rising; they are building tiny fortresses so they don't get eaten by the rising tide. The point isn't to fix the Titanic; the point is to ensure that when the water hits, there are still a few",
